750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*vcXVoc8mDBdQxsGhzTxTTA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*vcXVoc8mDBdQxsGhzTxTTA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*vcXVoc8mDBdQxsGhzTxTTA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*vcXVoc8mDBdQxsGhzTxTTA.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*vcXVoc8mDBdQxsGhzTxTTA.png"></picture></div><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content4 cid-tt5SM2WLsM" id="content4-2" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="row justify-content-center">
                    <div class="title col-md-12 col-lg-9">
                        <h3 class="mbr-section-title mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-2">
                            <strong>The Next Time You’re Feeling Angry or Hurt by Something Someone Said, Try Doing Something New — Absolutely Nothing</h3></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">#complextraumadoc</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">That’s right. Before you respond, take some time to consider your options.*</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Most people find holding their tongue challenging if they’re angry or hurt. If you’ve experienced complex trauma, it might feel impossible to remain silent — your boundaries have been violated in ways that compromised your safety and integrity. The moment you sense danger, the defenses go up — you snap back at the other person. It happens so fast that it feels like a reflex — no thinking involved, just whack! The words are flying out of your mouth.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If these disputes left everyone feeling better, there wouldn’t be much to worry about. But what’s likely to happen is that you say something even worse, increasing the likelihood that the other person will snap back at you in return. In an escalating situation like this, you’re both going to feel more and more out of control. Things can quickly become unsafe.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Not everyone living with complex trauma snaps back. Instead, many people respond by burying their emotions and pretending everything is okay. Some even go as far as to agree with the harsh words being lobbed against them. While these two approaches might seem markedly different, they share one thing in common — they are both automatic, learned responses.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Traumatic experiences hone our threat detectors to the degree that we are constantly scanning the environment for trouble. That’s how single incidents become generalized, causing assumptions and preconceived ideas to infiltrate sometimes innocent, everyday interactions.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Seeing Monsters Everywhere — The Topsy-turvy World of Dissociation</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If you’re a trauma survivor, no doubt you’ve tried to make sense of the motives of the person who harmed you. While there might have been recognizable patterns to their abuse, there remains an inherent illogic to the motivations of abusers. This illogic can often be traced to the experience of dissociation.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Many people who become abusers were themselves abused. As a result, they are likely to experience PTSD-related dissociative states — particularly in moments when they are harming others. Attempting to make sense of a situation where the other person is in a dissociative state — and potentially causing you to dissociate — leads to a place where no logic is to be found. It also leads to misguided assumptions about why people lash out. Even in low-stakes situations, a trauma survivor who is the recipient of a hurtful comment is prone to reflexively applying strategies developed in the context of their traumatic experience.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">It’s All About Self-protection</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In a rational frame of mind, this all might make perfect sense, but trauma doesn’t just exist in the realm of thoughts — it is also imprinted onto feeling states and in the body’s tissues. When you attempt to take some time to think about your options, your heart is likely to overwhelm your head. That’s precisely why you need to take a break. Your heart — and entire body — need to reset after threat-induced hormones like adrenaline and cortisol are released. Blood used to nourish your prefrontal cortex — the seat of the brain’s executive functioning — is siphoned off to mobilize your limbs for fight or flight when a threat is perceived. If you’ve experienced dissociative states as a result of PTSD, then you might also be feeling a sense of disembodiment and detachment from reality when you are on the receiving end of a hurtful comment.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In these topsy-turvy states, it makes sense that a traumatized person would seek to protect themselves by cutting off the threatening person as quickly as possible. A verbal smackdown or total acquiescence may do the job in the short term, but what about the long game? Assumptions and automatic reactions might cause you to alienate someone who might one day become an ally. Acquiescence might encourage the offender to think that you agree with them, leading to more hurtful comments.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">How To Handle Things Differently</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">First, you need to create some space between yourself and the other person. Tell them you need time to think about what they’ve just said. Next, find a quiet place where you can ground yourself. An exercise like progressive muscle relaxation is great for calming your body and mind. There are tons of YouTube videos to take you through the basics, but it essentially involves sequentially tensing and releasing muscle groups. When you’re feeling threatened or experiencing symptoms of dissociation, progressive muscle relaxation helps to slow racing thoughts and bring you back into your body.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">After you’ve spent some time grounding yourself, utilize this checklist to help navigate your options. Make sure to write down your responses. After you’ve finished, put it to the side and go back and add additional thoughts as they come up.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Step 1: Brainstorming</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What feelings came up when you heard the hurtful comment?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If these feelings are familiar, what do you associate them with? When was the earliest time (or incident) when you recall feeling this way?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What do these feelings tell you about yourself? Put these feelings into a list labeled “Beliefs About Myself.”</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What do these feelings tell you about others? Put these feelings into a list labeled “Beliefs About the World.”</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What assumptions might you be making based on these beliefs?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Develop 3–4 alternative explanations to counter each of your beliefs about yourself and the world.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What is at stake for you in this situation?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What has your role contributed to this situation?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Are you avoiding asserting your needs? What do you fear if you make your needs known?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Are you trying to hurt the other person to make them feel worse than they made you feel? If so, what do you hope to achieve in the long term?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What would be a realistic ideal outcome in this dispute for you? How about the other person?</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Step 2: Preparation</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Talk over the above items with someone you trust. What are their views? Did you learn anything new?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Develop a list of possible responses and write down the pros and cons of each strategy.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Pick your top choice and tell the offender you’d like to speak with them.</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Step 3: Implementation</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">During the discussion, stick with your strategy.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Avoid statements like “you always…” or “you never…”</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Use “I” statements as in “I felt this way when you…” rather than “You know that’s how I’d feel…”</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Avoid vocalizing blanket judgments about the other person.</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Step 4: Reflection</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ul><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">After the discussion, assess how things went.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What have you learned?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Are there things you could do differently next time?</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Did you miss any opportunities or overlook possible strategies in your preparation for the discussion?</li></ul></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Above all, remember to be compassionate towards yourself during this process. You may sometimes get it wrong, but being intentional about disrupting long-standing patterns will help steer you in the right direction. If you want to learn more, check out my new book <a href="https://raabandco.com/daddy" target="_self">Daddy</a>, where I delve into questions like who’s responsible when violence is committed in the midst of a dissociative episode and how survivors of complex trauma find stability and meaning in their lives.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Tell me what you think. Do you have trouble handling situations like these? Anything I’ve left out?</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">*If you are in a violent relationship, these strategies are not for you. For confidential help contact the National Domestic Violence Hotline at 800–799–7233 or online at <a href="https://www.thehotline.org/" target="_self">https://www.thehotline.org/</a></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">This article is for general information purposes only. It is not intended to be a substitute for specific medical or mental health advice.</p></div></div></div></section><?php include_once 'Elemental/footer.php'; ?>